Class LazyMultiset<T>

  • Object
    • ConcurrentMultiset<T>
      • LazyMultiset<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Multiset<T>

    public class LazyMultiset<T>
extends ConcurrentMultiset<T>
    An implementation of a concurrent Multiset whose underlying data structure is a linked list composed of independently-lockable nodes. The nodes are locked only when performing operations that modify the multiset, and only at the locus of modification; additional measures must be taken to ensure consistency when performing a read-only operation concurrently with a modification.
    Author:
    Orlando Leombruni
    See Also:
    Multiset, ConcurrentMultiset

      • add

        public int add(T element,
               int occurrences)
        throws IllegalArgumentException,
               FullSetException
        Adds multiple occurrences of the specified element into the multiset.

        This method uses the find method to transverse the underlying list and then locks the elements at the point of the insertion/modification.

        Note that if a RemoveAll operation is currently being executed, this method waits for its completion before doing anything.

        Parameters:
        element - The element to be inserted.
        occurrences - The number of occurrences.
        Returns:
        The number of occurrences of the element that were present in the multiset before this operation (zero if the element wasn't in the multiset).
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If element == null or occurrences is 0 or less.
        FullSetException - If this operation causes the multiset to grow beyond its maximum capacity.

      • removeAll

        public boolean removeAll(Collection<?> c)
                  throws IllegalArgumentException
        Removes from the multiset all the elements which are both in the collection passed as argument and in the multiset itself.

        This method scans the entire list from head to tail, without locking any node; meanwhile, it builds a new list. For every element of the original list:

        • if the element is contained n >= 1 times in the collection, and the current count for that element is m > n, then the method adds to the new list the element with (m - n) occurrences;
        • if the element is contained n >= 1 times in the collection, and the current count for that element is m <= n, then the method won't add the current element to the new list;
        • if the element is not contained in the collection, it is copied into the new list as is.

        At the end, the method sets the new list as the representation of the multiset.

        Note that the implementation is virtually identical to the LockFreeMultiset one, as neither implementation makes use of locks or other implementation-dependent features.

        Executing this method will put the multiset in a read-only state for the entire duration of its execution. While in this state, Add, Remove and other RemoveAll calls will be queued, while Count, Contains and Size calls will be executed as normal on the old state of the multiset, before the start of the execution of RemoveAll.

        Parameters:
        c - The collection containing the elements to be removed from the multiset.
        Returns:
        true if the multiset has been modified by this operation (at least one element was removed).
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If the collection passed as an argument is a null pointer.
